Email: seanzhu@csu.edu.cn and ywduan66@sina.com The Chinese Ministry of Education 111 Project, Grant/Award Number: BP0820034; The Fundamental Research Funds for the Central Universities of Central South University (CSU), Grant/Award Number: 2019zzts331; The National Natural Science Foundation of China, Grant/Award Numbers: 81530092, 81872779 The rubromycins (RUBs) family natural products (Figure 1) are a group of complex aromatic polyketides isolated from various actinomycetes (Atkinson & Brimble, 2015; Harunari et al., 2014; 2019), which possess a typical molecular scaffold consisting of a naphthoquinone ring with an isocoumarin ring through a 5,6‐spiroketal system. Besides the broad‐ spectrum antibiotic activity against Gram‐positive bacteria and fungi, Supporting information: Additional description, tables, figures about experimental details, and HRMS, NMR spectra of compounds 1 and 7. Biotechnol Bioeng. 2021;1–12. Abstract β‐rubromycin (β‐RUB) (1) is an efficient inhibitor of human telomerase possessing a

unique spiroketal moiety as a potential pharmacophore and regarded as a promising anticancer drug lead. But the development of (β‐RUB) (1) has long been hampered by its low titer and very poor water solubility. By adopting a genome mining strategy, an FAD‐dependent monooxygenase RubN involving with the formation of the spiro system was applied as the probe and Streptomyces sp. CB00271 was screened out from our strain collection as an alternative natural high producer of β‐RUB (1). After a series of fermentation optimizations, CB00271 could produce 124.8 ± 3.4 mg/L β‐RUB (1), which was the highest titer up to now. Moreover, the enhanced production of β‐RUB (1) in fermentation broth also led to the discovery of a new congener β‐RUB acid (7), which was structurally elucidated as the acid form of β‐RUB (1). Comparing to β‐RUB (1), the substituted carboxyl group endowed β‐RUB acid (7) much better solubility in serum and resulted in its higher activity towards tumor cells. Our work set up a solid base for the pilot‐scale production of β‐RUB (1) and its congeners to facilitate their future development as promising anticancer drug leads, and also provide an alternative and practical strategy for the exploita- tion of other important microbial natural products. antitumor activity, genome mining, novel rubromycin congener, solubility, titer improvement, β‐rubromycin wileyonlinelibrary.com/journal/bit some of the RUBs, such as β‐rubromycin (β‐RUB) (1), γ‐rubromycin (γ‐RUB) (2), and griseorhodins (GRHs), also presented special biological properties as the potent inhibitors towards human telomerase and retroviral reverse transcriptase (Handley, 1990). Among them, β‐RUB (1) contained a distinct tautomerized naphthoquinone ring different from other RUBs (Figure 1) and showed the highest inhibition potency

on telomerase (Mizushina et al., 2012). Since telomerase is highly ex- pressed in most tumor cells and crucial to the maintenance of their © 2021 Wiley Periodicals LLC hyaluromycin [HYL]) [Color figure can be viewed at wileyonlinelibrary.com] telomere length for long‐term survival, it has been regarded as a pro- mising target for anticancer drug development (Ogawa et al., 2008; Rezler et al., 2003; Saraswati et al., 2019). Therefore, β‐RUB (1) is a potential lead compound for the development of novel drugs to cope with the increasing global health threats caused by cancer or epidemic viral infections. Despite the early discovery, the exploitation of β‐RUB (1) has long been hampered by its limited natural supply and extremely low solubility in common solvents (Boumehira et al., 2016; Yunt et al., 2009). The chemical syntheses of RUBs, especially the spiroketal core, are involved with many complex transformations and very chal- lenging. Although the total synthesis of racemic γ‐RUB (2) has been fulfilled (Rathwell et al., 2009; Wilsdorf & Reissig, 2014; Wu et al., 2011), the reported overall yields were only about 4% and not optically pure, while a synthetic route accessing β‐RUB (1) has not been achieved so far. On the other hand, the practical preparation of β‐RUB (1) through microbial fermentation was restricted by its existing low titers in different strains (Atkinson & Brimble, 2015; Boumehira et al., 2016). Recently, a new RUB member hyaluromycin (HYL) has been discovered from a marine‐derived Streptomyces The structures of rubromycins family of natural products (rubromycin [RUB], heliquinomycin [HLQ], griseorhodin [GRH], (Shiro et al., 2016), and two new congeners RUB CA1 (3) and CA2 have

also been isolated afterward (Harunari et al., 2019), suggesting the biosynthetic potential of Streptomyces in RUBs production. Therefore, finding more potential RUB producing strains, alternative high producer of β‐RUB (1) in particular, shall help us to break the application bot- tleneck of β‐RUB (1) or even find new RUB lead compounds to facilitate their future development. important drug leads are still the main challenges in the development of microbial natural products. With the advancement of genome sequencing and the comprehensive understandings of natural pro- duct biosyntheses, genome mining has become a powerful and effi- cient approach to thoroughly explore the biosynthetic potentials of various microorganisms. By using varied pathway‐specific probes, this strategy has been successfully applied for the discovery of novel natural products, such as the enediynes (Yan et al., 2016; 2017), the leinamycin family of compounds (Pan et al., 2017) and etc. More importantly, such a strategy has also provided a feasible way to find more alternative producers The discovery of novel candidates and titer improvement of antitumor C‐1027 and antiinfective platensimycin for instance (Hindra et al. (2014); Yan et al., 2018). Typical strain improvement or/and medium optimization have been extensively applied to en- hance the production of desired compounds, while the mother nat- ure may already acclimate some talent strains through million years of evolution to achieve the same purpose. The availability of alter- native producers enabled us to circumvent common deficiencies of original wild‐type strains, such as low production titers, unfavorable growth, and poor genetic amenability et al (Krug & Muller, 2014), which shall greatly facilitate subsequent practical development of desired natural products. Among discovered 20 RUBs, only the biosynthetic gene clusters (BGCs) of β‐RUB (1) (rub), GRH (grh), HYL (hyl) and heliquinomycin

et al., 2009; Zhuang et al., 2020). Although RUBs are derived from a Type‐II polyketide synthase pathway, their post tailoring steps re- main elusive, especially the tautomerization of β‐RUB (1). The 5,6‐spiroketal core is a conservative functional group critical for the unique activities of RUBs on telomerase and reverse tran- scriptase (Ueno et al., 2000). Since α‐rubromycin (α‐RUB) (4), the open‐ring derivative of β‐RUB (1) losing such spiroketal system, is comparably inactive towards these enzymes. The biosynthetic stu- dies about GRHs revealed that a FAD‐dependent monooxygenase (FDM) GrhO6 was directly involved in the formation of the spiro system (Yunt et al., 2009) and its homologs are extensively found in reported BGCs of other RUBs. Therefore, it is feasible to apply FDM as a probe for genome mining of potential RUB producers. NCBI database by using RubN (the homolog of GrhO6) as the probe. A total of 54 potential RUB‐type BGCs were screened out, while 2 of them were derived from S sp. CB00271 and S sp. CB04723 in our bacterial strain library. Further metabolite characterization validated CB00271 as a β‐RUB (1) producer and CB04723 as a GRH producer. More importantly, the obtained titer of β‐RUB (1) in CB00271 was over 120 mg/L after simple fermentation optimization, representing the highest yield so far in contrast to reported values. Such sig- nificant titer improvement also led to the discovery of a new con- gener β‐RUB acid (7), which presented much better solubility in serum and resulted in higher activity towards tumor cells. Our re- sults established a solid base for the future development of RUB derived drug leads, and also provided a reference for industrial ex- ploitation of other important microbial natural products. 2 | M A TE RIALS AND ME THO D S 2.1 | General experimental procedures All chemical and biological reagents were purchased from common

2.2 | Sequence similarity network (SSN) analysis of FDM genes in GenBank By using RubN (AAM97364.1) as the query, the BlastP search in the nonredundant protein sequence database of NCBI (until September 10, 2020) was carried out and downloaded 1799 FDM sequences. To re- move the duplicate or highly similar (>90%) FDM sequences, 1799 FDM sequences were winnowed into 867 representative sequences by filtering to a maximum identity of 90% using CD‐HIT and built an FDM database using formatdb command in Blast+. To construct the SSN, each sequence was used as a query to search the whole FDM database using BlastP. The Blast E‐value threshold was set at 1.0 × 10−180 based on the lowest sequence similarity, under which all characterized FDM sequences could be grouped into a single cluster. The edges formed from self‐loops between each node itself and those from duplicates between two nodes were deleted from the network. The resulting SSN analysis was visualized using the organic layout in Cytoscape 4.1 (Kohl et al., 2011). The alignment of concatenated housekeeping genes was generated using ClustalW. Phylogenetic analysis was performed using MEGA 7.0.18 (Kumar et al., 2016). The antitumor activity of β‐RUB (1), γ‐RUB (2), RUB CA1 (3), and β‐RUB acid (7), as well as the positive control BLM‐sulfate, were re- spectively evaluated in four different human tumor cell lines (A549, HepG2, Caco‐2, and Hela) by the standard CCK‐8 assay (Xiong et al., 2020). Briefly, cells were seeded in 96‐well plates with 4 × 103 cells per well and stabilized for 24 h. Then cells were treated with a certain agent at different concentrations in 100 µl media per well. After 72 h of incubation, 10 µL of CCK‐8 reagent (Zeta Life Inc.) was added into each well and incubated at 37°C for 1–2 h. Cell viability was evaluated by the measurement of absorbance at 450 nm using a microplate reader (Spark 10 M; Tecan). All experiments were carried out in triplicate. The residual serum samples from CCK8 assays were also respectively applied at 4 and 24 h to measure the relative solubility of target RUB compounds in serum. Each sample was cen- trifuged, and the real soluble amount of the target RUB compound in the supernatant was determined by HPLC quantification. The relative solubility was defined as the ratio of the concentration quantified by HPLC to the theoretical concentration from agent dilution. 3 | RES ULTS A ND DIS C USSION 3.1 | Genome mining of the rubromycins family of natural products using RubN as the probe The FDMs from all known BGCs of RUBs (RUB‐FDM) including GrhO6, RubN, HlqO6, and HylO6 shared very high similarity and above 73% identity (data not shown), therefore RubN encoded in rub was applied as the query to obtain potential FDMs over the threshold of 45% se- quence identity from NCBI nonredundant genome database. The homology searches afforded 1799 FDMs (as of September 10, 2020)

and then clustered into 867 representative sequences with a 90% identity cutoff. The subsequent SSN analysis at an E‐value threshold of 1 × 10−180 further grouped these 867 FDM candidates into 11 major clusters, with a sequence identity of about 70% in each cluster (Figure 2a). The SSN analysis revealed that all four known RUB‐FDMs were gathered in cluster G together with other eight uncharacterized FDMs, which represented a total of 58 homologous FDMs from dif- ferent strains encompassing four varied genera (Table S1). The taxo- nomic distribution of these strains showed that nearly 93% of them belonging to Streptomyces (Figure 2b), a class of prolific producers for biologically active natural products. The phylogenetic analysis of 4 RUB‐FDMs with 54 homologous proteins indicated that 31 and 10 of FDM homologues were respectively clustered into the GrhO6 and RubN clades, while the HylO6 clade showed the highest species di- versity (Figure 2c). Interestingly, the 12 representative FDMs obtained from SSN analysis were evenly distributed in all phylogenetic clades only except GrhO6, which suggested possible varieties in these clades. Through the above optimizations, the production of 7 was also enhanced in the absence of resins. The accumulations of β‐RUB (1) and 7 were monitored every day during the entire fermen- tation period (Figure S5a). We observed that the biosynthesis of β‐RUB (1) was initiated very early on the second day and its content reached the maximum on the third day for about 87.7 ± 1.1 mg/L. The appearance of 7 was detected on the fourth day and its concentration was gradually increased over time along with the reduced content of β‐RUB (1), which suggested a certain conversion between them. Both concentrations of β‐RUB (1) and 7 were comparably stable since the sixth day, which were 74.2 ± 3.0 and 13.6 ± 0.7 mg/L, respectively. Besides, the pro- duction and changes of these two compounds might be related to the pH of fermentation broth since this value was steadily in- creased from 7.0 to 8.5 during the fermentation (Figure S5a), and the possible conversion from β‐RUB (1) to 7 was clearly observed over pH 7.5 (Figure 6a I–III). When the pH of the final fermen- tation broth was further adjusted, we happened to found that the direct acidification up to pH 3.5 led to the complete precipitation of RUB compounds in broth, and the resulted purplish‐red pre- cipitates could be redissolved to easily enrich target RUB com- pounds (Figure 6a IV–VI). The transformation from β‐RUB (1) to 7 could be observed at pH 11 and fully completed after 12 h incubation (Figure 6a VII–VIII), while a similar conversion from γ‐RUB (2) to RUB CA1 (3) was also detected, all of which were likely the alkaline hydrolysis of esters. However, our attempts to obtain 7 through the direct alkaline hydrolysis of pure β‐RUB (1) were unsatisfactory, because the trials in alkaline methanol was limited by the poor solubility of substance while in alkaline

DMSO was failed due to the complete degradation of compounds (Figure S5b). Therefore, 7 could only be obtained through fer- mentation and subsequent direct alkaline transformation so far. After isolation and purification, 7 was obtained as purple powder, formula established as C26H18O12 by with the molecular HRESI‐MS analysis (Figure S6). The 1H and 13C NMR spectra of 7 were very similar to those of β‐RUB (1) only except the signal of the end oxymethyl group was missing (Figure S9–S10 and Table 2), which suggested a carboxyl group at C‐7 of 7 instead of a carboxyl methyl ester (Figure 6b), hence 7 was named β‐RUB acid (7). It had been reported that β‐RUB (1) can be quickly transformed into γ‐RUB (2) under acidic conditions (Puder et al., 2010), and we found such transformation was indeed oc- curred when β‐RUB (1) was treated with 1 M HCl in DMSO for a while (Figure S5c). Coincidently, the conversion from β‐RUB acid (7) to RUB CA1 (3) was also occurred under the same condition (Figure S5d), which further validated the structure of β‐RUB 3.5 | The improved solubility of β‐RUB acid (7) in serum led to its better antitumor activity The in vitro antitumor activities of β‐RUB (1), γ‐RUB (2), RUB CA1 (3), and β‐RUB acid (7) were respectively evaluated against four different human cancer cell lines, including the nonsmall cell lung cancer cell line A549, the liver hepatocellular carcinoma HepG2, the cervical cancer cell line Hela, and the colon tumor cell line Caco‐2 (Xiong et al., 2020). During the assays, the distinct purple precipitate of β‐RUB (1) or γ‐RUB (2) was clearly observed in serum under high concentrations (data not shown), therefore the relative solubilities of

four compounds in serum were first determined based on the quantitative HPLC analyses. The results showed that β‐RUB (1) and γ‐RUB (2) were poorly dissolved in serum, their saturated solubilities were around 10–20 μM and continuously decreased over time. In contrast, the saturated solubilities of RUB CA1 (3) and β‐RUB acid (7) were notably increased up to 60–70 μM and stable (Figure 7). Comparing to β‐RUB (1) and γ‐RUB (2), their corresponding acid form congeners RUB CA1 (3) and β‐RUB acid (7) presented sig- nificantly enhanced antitumor potencies against all tested tumor cells, in which their activities towards A549, Hela, and Caco‐2 cells were improved for about at least one order, and the antitumor ac- tivity of β‐RUB acid (7) was better than that of RUB CA1 (3) (Table 1). The inferior activity increment of RUB CA1 (3) or β‐RUB acid (7) on HepG2 cells may be attributed to the lower positive ratio of telomerase activity in HepG2 cells (about 75%) comparing with the other three cell lines (over 90%) (Chen & Chen, 2011; Saini et al., 2009). Overall, our preliminary results suggested that the terminal carboxyl group contributed to the improved solubility and antitumor activity of RUB compounds, therefore RUB CA1 (3) and β‐RUB acid (7), especially the latter, could be the better leads for T A B L E 2 The cytotoxicities of β‐RUB (1), γ‐RUB (2), RUB CA1 (3), β‐RUB acid (7), and BLM‐sulfate against selected four human tumor cell linesa different reserve time (4 h or 24 h) at room temperature. RUB, rubromycin [Color figure can be viewed at wileyonlinelibrary.com] In summary, S sp. CB00271 was successfully screened out as an alternative natural producer of β‐RUB (1), through a genome mining

strategy by using RubN as the probe. After fermentation optimiza- tion, the production of β‐RUB (1) in CB00271 was over 120 mg/L and became the highest reported titer so far. Besides, the enhanced biosynthetic capacity of RUBs in CB00271 also enables us to dis- cover a new congener β‐RUB acid (7), which possessed the much better serum solubility and the resulted higher antitumor activity than those of β‐RUB (1). The good genetic amenability of CB00271 and the unique genes contained in rubCB00271, as well as the im- proved titer of RUBs, established a solid base for deciphering the biosynthesis of β‐RUB (1) and future development of RUB derived drug leads. Moreover, our work also provided an alternative strategy and offered a reference for the exploitation of other important mi- crobial natural products.
